  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Money Laundering and Financial Crimes Strategy Act\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 - Laundering of monetary instruments\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 - Engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity\n\n3. State Level:\n- Many states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n\n4. International Cooperation:\n- The U.S. works with international organizations like FATF (Financial Action Task Force) to combat money laundering\n\nThese statutes generally:\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Criminalize the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money\n- Impose significant penalties including fines and imprisonment\n- Establish reporting and record-keeping requirements for financial institutions\n\nThe laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
